    earlyLife: 'Born in Saint-Germain-en-Laye near Paris, Debussy entered the Paris Conservatoire at age ten. A rebellious student, he frustrated his professors by breaking harmonic rules — foreshadowing the revolutionary path his music would take. In 1884, he won the prestigious Prix de Rome, though he found his time in Italy stifling.',
    career: 'Debussy rejected the label "Impressionist," yet his music perfectly captures the movement\'s ideals — light, color, and atmosphere over rigid structure. His innovations in harmony, including the use of whole-tone and pentatonic scales, parallel chords, and unresolved dissonances, freed music from the tyranny of traditional tonality and paved the way for the modern era.',
