    intro: 'Maurice Ravel was a French composer whose meticulous craftsmanship and brilliant orchestrations made him one of the most important figures in early 20th-century music. Often grouped with the Impressionists, Ravel defied easy categorization, blending classical precision with exotic harmonies, jazz influences, and an unmatched gift for orchestral color.',
    earlyLife: 'Born in Ciboure in the Basque region of France, Ravel moved to Paris as an infant. His father, a Swiss engineer with a love of music, encouraged his early studies. He entered the Paris Conservatoire at age fourteen, where he studied under Gabriel Fauré and developed his distinctive, polished style.',
    career: 'Ravel composed relatively few works compared to his contemporaries, but each was polished to perfection. His orchestrations are considered the finest ever written — his arrangement of Mussorgsky\'s Pictures at an Exhibition surpasses the original in fame. He drew from Spanish music, jazz, and Asian scales, creating a unique sonic palette that ranged from the intimate Miroirs to the overwhelming power of Boléro.',
    legacy: 'Ravel\'s orchestral mastery influenced generations of film composers and orchestrators. His ability to build tension through repetition (as in Boléro) and his shimmering harmonic language set a new standard for tonal color. Alongside Debussy, he defined the sound of early 20th-century French music, yet his precision and classical structures set him apart as a unique voice.',
