    tagline: 'The Czech master who brought folk music to the concert hall',
    intro: 'Antonín Dvořák rose from a small Bohemian village to become one of the most celebrated composers of the late 19th century. His music radiates warmth, rhythmic vitality, and a deep love of Czech and Slavic folk traditions, combined with a command of symphonic form that earned the admiration of Brahms and audiences worldwide.',
    earlyLife: 'Born in Nelahozeves, Bohemia, Dvořák was the son of a butcher and innkeeper. He studied organ and composition at the Prague Organ School and spent years playing viola in the Provisional Theatre Orchestra, absorbing the operatic and symphonic repertoire while composing in obscurity.',
    career: 'Dvořák\'s breakthrough came when Brahms recommended his Moravian Duets to the publisher Simrock. The Slavonic Dances that followed made him an international star. His American years (1892–1895) produced the "New World" Symphony and the Cello Concerto, two of the most popular works in the repertoire. He drew inspiration from spirituals and Native American music in America, while never abandoning his Czech roots.',
    legacy: 'Dvořák proved that national folk idioms could be woven into the highest forms of Western classical music. His "New World" Symphony remains one of the most performed symphonies in the world, and his Cello Concerto is widely regarded as the greatest ever written for the instrument. He inspired generations of Czech composers and showed that musical nationalism and universal appeal could coexist beautifully.',
