    tagline: 'The last great Romantic whose piano concertos conquered the world',
    intro: 'Sergei Rachmaninoff was a towering figure of early 20th-century music — equally celebrated as a composer, pianist, and conductor. His sweeping melodies, lush harmonies, and formidable virtuosity made him the last great voice of Russian Romanticism. His piano concertos and symphonies remain among the most beloved and frequently performed works in the classical repertoire.',
    earlyLife: 'Born into a musical family near Novgorod, Russia, Rachmaninoff entered the Moscow Conservatory at age nine. He studied under the strict discipline of Nikolai Zverev and later with Arensky and Taneyev. He graduated with the Great Gold Medal in 1892, having already composed his famous Prelude in C-sharp minor.',
    career: 'After the catastrophic premiere of his First Symphony in 1897, Rachmaninoff fell into a deep creative crisis that lasted three years. Hypnotherapy helped him recover, and his Piano Concerto No. 2 marked a glorious return. He left Russia after the 1917 Revolution and spent his remaining years in the West, concertizing relentlessly as a pianist while composing sparingly but magnificently. His enormous hands — reportedly able to span a 13th on the keyboard — became legendary.',
