    id: 'mahler', fullName: 'Gustav Mahler', years: '1860–1911', birthYear: 1860, deathYear: 1911,
    genre: 'Classical', nationality: 'Austrian', era: 'Late Romantic',
    tagline: 'The symphony must be like the world — it must contain everything.',
    intro: 'Gustav Mahler was an Austrian late-Romantic composer and one of the leading conductors of his generation. His music bridges the 19th-century Austro-German tradition with the modernism of the early 20th century. His ten symphonies and his song cycles for voice and orchestra are among the most performed works in the concert repertoire today, celebrated for their vast emotional range, philosophical ambition, and orchestral brilliance.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on July 7, 1860, in Kaliště, Bohemia (then part of the Austrian Empire), Mahler was the second of fourteen children in a Jewish family. His musical talent was evident early; he gave his first public piano recital at age ten. In 1875, he enrolled at the Vienna Conservatory, where he studied piano, harmony, and composition. He also attended lectures at the University of Vienna, absorbing philosophy and literature that would profoundly shape his artistic vision.',
    career: 'Mahler\'s dual career as composer and conductor made him one of the most influential musicians of his era. As director of the Vienna Court Opera for a decade, he raised performance standards to new heights and staged landmark productions. His summers were devoted to composing in rural retreats — first at Steinbach am Attersee, then at Maiernigg on the Wörthersee, and finally at Toblach. His symphonies grew ever larger in scope, from the nature-inspired early works to the vast spiritual dramas of his middle period and the intensely personal late works. His orchestral song cycles — <em>Das Lied von der Erde</em>, <em>Kindertotenlieder</em>, and the <em>Rückert-Lieder</em> — fuse voice and orchestra with unparalleled intimacy.',
    legacy: 'Largely overlooked for decades after his death, Mahler\'s music experienced a dramatic revival in the 1960s, championed by conductors like Leonard Bernstein and Georg Solti. Today his symphonies are cornerstones of the orchestral repertoire worldwide. His influence extends far beyond the concert hall — his emotional directness, use of irony and quotation, and radical juxtaposition of the sublime and the banal paved the way for composers from Shostakovich to Britten and anticipated many techniques of postmodernism. His famous declaration, "My time will come," proved prophetic.',
