    id: 'shostakovich', fullName: 'Dmitri Shostakovich', years: '1906–1975', birthYear: 1906, deathYear: 1975,
    genre: 'Classical', nationality: 'Russian', era: '20th Century',
    tagline: 'A creative reply to just criticism.',
    intro: 'Dmitri Shostakovich was the foremost Soviet composer and one of the most significant musical voices of the 20th century. Working under the constant scrutiny of the Stalinist regime, he produced a vast body of work — 15 symphonies, 15 string quartets, concertos, operas, and film scores — that ranges from public triumph to private anguish. His music is celebrated for its emotional intensity, biting irony, and the extraordinary skill with which he navigated the perilous boundary between artistic integrity and political survival.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on September 25, 1906, in Saint Petersburg, Russia, Shostakovich showed exceptional musical gifts from childhood. His mother, a professional pianist, gave him his first piano lessons at age nine. By thirteen he had entered the Petrograd Conservatory, studying piano and composition. His graduation piece, the Symphony No. 1, premiered in 1926 when he was just nineteen and brought him immediate international acclaim, announcing the arrival of a major new talent.',
    career: 'Shostakovich\'s career was defined by the tension between his artistic ambitions and the demands of the Soviet state. After the devastating Pravda attack of 1936, he withdrew his Symphony No. 4 and responded with the outwardly triumphant Fifth. Throughout World War II, he composed music of patriotic fervor, including the famous "Leningrad" Symphony. After the war, he faced further denunciation in the Zhdanov decree of 1948. His later works grew increasingly introspective: the final string quartets and the Symphony No. 14 confront death with unflinching directness. Whether writing for film, the concert hall, or the intimate chamber setting, his music possesses an unmistakable voice — sardonic, tragic, and profoundly human.',
    legacy: 'Shostakovich remains one of the most performed and debated composers of the 20th century. His 15 symphonies constitute the most important symphonic cycle since Mahler, and his 15 string quartets stand alongside Beethoven\'s and Bartók\'s as pinnacles of the form. The question of whether his music represents genuine Soviet loyalty or covert dissidence continues to fuel scholarly debate, but the power of the music itself is beyond dispute. His influence can be heard in composers from Schnittke to John Adams, and his works continue to speak with searing relevance to audiences worldwide.',
