    tagline: 'The eccentric visionary who invented ambient music a century before its time',
    intro: 'Erik Satie was one of the most original and enigmatic figures in the history of Western music. A composer, pianist, and self-styled “phonometrician,” he rejected Romantic excess in favor of stripped-down clarity, absurdist humor, and radical simplicity. His influence reaches far beyond classical music into ambient, minimalism, and experimental art.',
    earlyLife: 'Born in Honfleur, Normandy, in 1866, Satie moved to Paris at age 12 after his mother\'s death. He enrolled at the Paris Conservatoire but was considered lazy and untalented by his professors. He dropped out, drifted into the bohemian world of Montmartre, and began playing piano at the cabaret Le Chat Noir, where he developed his unique aesthetic vision.',
    career: 'Satie composed music that defied every convention of his time. He gave pieces absurdist titles like “Three Pieces in the Shape of a Pear” and “Dried Embryos.” His scores contained whimsical instructions for performers such as “play like a nightingale with a toothache.” Yet beneath the humor lay profound innovation: his concept of “furniture music” anticipated ambient music by decades, and his harmonic language influenced Debussy, Ravel, and the group of composers known as Les Six.',
    legacy: 'Once dismissed as an eccentric dilettante, Satie is now recognized as one of the most forward-thinking composers in history. His Gymnopédies are among the most-streamed classical piano works today. His concept of background music anticipated Brian Eno\'s ambient experiments by 60 years. John Cage cited him as a primary influence, and minimalist composers from Philip Glass to Steve Reich owe a clear debt to his aesthetic of radical simplicity.',
