    tagline: 'The most prolific composer in jazz history',
    intro: 'Edward Kennedy "Duke" Ellington was an American composer, pianist, and bandleader whose career spanned more than 50 years. He composed thousands of pieces — from three-minute singles to suites, film scores, sacred concerts, and a musical — making him the most prolific and arguably the greatest composer in jazz history. His sophisticated orchestrations elevated jazz from dance-hall entertainment to a respected art form.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on April 29, 1899, in Washington, D.C., Edward Kennedy Ellington grew up in a middle-class African American household. His father James was a butler who occasionally worked at the White House, instilling in young Edward a sense of elegance that would later earn him the nickname "Duke." He began piano lessons at age seven and was drawn to ragtime pianists he heard in the pool halls of Washington. By his teens, he was playing professionally at local venues, turning down an art scholarship to the Pratt Institute to pursue music full-time.',
    career: 'Ellington\'s Cotton Club years (1927–1932) made him a household name through nightly radio broadcasts. His "jungle sound" — featuring growling brass and exotic timbres — was unlike anything in jazz. He attracted brilliant soloists and wrote pieces tailored to each musician\'s unique voice, treating his orchestra as his instrument. The partnership with arranger-composer Billy Strayhorn, beginning in 1939, produced some of the greatest music in the American songbook. Ellington composed prolifically until his death, writing sacred concerts, film scores, ballets, and extended suites that stretched jazz into new territory.',
    legacy: 'Duke Ellington\'s influence on American music is incalculable. He elevated jazz from entertainment to art, broke racial barriers throughout his career, and created a body of work unmatched in scope and quality. His orchestra continued under his son Mercer after his death. Ellington received the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the French Legion of Honor, and a posthumous Pulitzer Prize Special Award. His compositions — from "Satin Doll" to "Sophisticated Lady" — remain cornerstones of the jazz repertoire and the Great American Songbook.',
