    tagline: 'The genius who invented bebop',
    intro: 'Charles Christopher Parker Jr. — known universally as "Bird" — was an American alto saxophonist who co-created bebop and fundamentally transformed the language of jazz. His astonishing speed, harmonic sophistication, and melodic inventiveness pushed improvisation to heights previously thought impossible. Despite a tragically short life ravaged by addiction, Parker\'s recordings remain among the most influential in all of music, and his compositions are essential standards in every jazz musician\'s repertoire.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on August 29, 1920, in Kansas City, Kansas, Charlie Parker grew up across the state line in Kansas City, Missouri — a wide-open town where jazz thrived in clubs that stayed open all night. He began playing alto saxophone at age eleven and dropped out of school at fifteen to pursue music full-time. The competitive Kansas City jam session scene was his crucible: after being laughed off the bandstand by drummer Jo Jones for not knowing his changes, Parker spent months in the Ozarks woodshedding obsessively, returning to Kansas City a transformed musician.',
    career: 'Parker and Dizzy Gillespie forged bebop in the early 1940s at after-hours jam sessions in Harlem clubs like Minton\'s Playhouse and Monroe\'s Uptown House. Their music — blazingly fast, harmonically daring, rhythmically complex — was a deliberate departure from the danceable swing that preceded it. Parker\'s alto saxophone solos on recordings like "Ko-Ko," "Ornithology," and "Confirmation" remain benchmarks of improvisational genius. He also recorded with strings, fulfilling a lifelong dream to blend jazz with classical textures. Despite constant battles with heroin addiction that undermined his health and career, his musical output in barely a decade reshaped jazz permanently.',
    legacy: 'Charlie Parker\'s influence on jazz cannot be overstated. He made bebop the foundation upon which all modern jazz is built, and virtually every jazz musician since — from John Coltrane to Ornette Coleman — has grappled with his innovations. His compositions like "Confirmation," "Anthropology," and "Yardbird Suite" remain essential standards. The Charlie Parker Jazz Festival is held annually in New York City, and the Birdland jazz club is named in his honor. He was posthumously awarded a Pulitzer Prize Special Citation in 2024, and his recordings continue to inspire new generations of musicians worldwide.',
