    intro: 'Billie Holiday, born Eleanora Fagan, was one of the most influential jazz vocalists of all time. Her singular phrasing, emotional intensity, and ability to inhabit a song transformed the art of jazz singing. Known as "Lady Day," she turned every performance into a deeply personal statement, influencing generations of singers across jazz, pop, and soul.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on April 7, 1915, in Philadelphia and raised in Baltimore, Billie Holiday endured a turbulent childhood marked by poverty and hardship. Her parents, Sadie Fagan and Clarence Holiday (a jazz guitarist), never married, and she was largely raised by relatives. As a teenager she moved to Harlem, New York, where she began singing in nightclubs. With no formal training, she developed her style by listening to recordings of Louis Armstrong and Bessie Smith, absorbing their phrasing and emotional directness.',
    career: 'Holiday\'s career spanned nearly three decades, from Harlem nightclubs to Carnegie Hall. Her collaborations with Lester Young, Teddy Wilson, and other swing-era giants produced some of the most emotionally resonant recordings in jazz. She had an uncanny ability to bend melodies, delay phrases, and infuse lyrics with raw feeling. Her voice, while not technically powerful, conveyed a depth of emotion that few could match. Songs like God Bless the Child and Strange Fruit showcased her range from tender vulnerability to fierce social commentary.',
    legacy: 'Billie Holiday\'s influence on vocal music is immeasurable. She transformed jazz singing from mere interpretation into deeply personal storytelling. Her phrasing influenced Frank Sinatra, who called her "the greatest single musical influence on me." She was posthumously inducted into the Grammy Hall of Fame multiple times and received the Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award in 1987. Time magazine named Strange Fruit the "song of the century" in 1999. Today, Holiday remains the gold standard for emotional authenticity in vocal performance.',
