    id: 'bessie-smith', fullName: 'Bessie Smith', years: '1894–1937', birthYear: 1894, deathYear: 1937,
    genre: 'Blues', nationality: 'American', era: 'Classic Blues',
    tagline: 'The Empress of the Blues — the greatest female blues singer who ever lived',
    intro: 'Bessie Smith was the most acclaimed blues singer of the 1920s and 1930s, a towering figure whose powerful contralto voice could fill a theater without a microphone. Known as the "Empress of the Blues," she sold millions of records, commanded enormous fees, and virtually saved Columbia Records from bankruptcy. Her emotional depth and vocal power set the standard for blues, jazz, and popular singing for generations to come.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on April 15, 1894, in Chattanooga, Tennessee, Bessie Smith grew up in extreme poverty. Her father, a part-time Baptist preacher, died when she was young, and her mother passed when Bessie was nine. Orphaned and raised by her oldest sister, she began singing on street corners for spare change as a child. In 1912, her brother Clarence arranged an audition with a traveling vaudeville troupe that included Ma Rainey, the "Mother of the Blues," who became her mentor and taught her the art of performing the blues on stage.',
    career: 'Bessie Smith\'s recording career began in 1923 when Columbia Records signed her, and her debut "Down Hearted Blues" was a smash. Over the next decade she recorded roughly 160 songs, often accompanied by the finest jazz musicians of the era, including Louis Armstrong, Coleman Hawkins, and Fletcher Henderson. Her voice was extraordinary — huge, rich, and capable of conveying anguish, humor, defiance, and tenderness with equal force. The Great Depression devastated the record industry and her career declined, but she was staging a comeback with swing-era recordings when she died in a car accident in 1937.',
    legacy: 'Bessie Smith\'s influence is vast and enduring. She was a direct inspiration to Billie Holiday, Mahalia Jackson, Dinah Washington, Janis Joplin, and countless other singers. Her recordings are considered among the finest examples of classic blues and early jazz vocal artistry. She was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1989 as an early influence, and the Grammy Hall of Fame has honored multiple recordings. Her fearless artistry — singing openly about sexuality, heartbreak, poverty, and independence — made her a pioneer of self-expression in American music.',
