    genre: 'Blues', nationality: 'American', era: 'Texas Blues',
    tagline: 'The Texas Tornado who reignited the blues',
    intro: 'Stevie Ray Vaughan was one of the most influential electric guitarists in blues history. With a tone that could shake walls and a vibrato that could make grown men weep, he almost single-handedly brought blues back into the mainstream during the 1980s. His tragically short career produced some of the most electrifying guitar music ever recorded, blending Texas blues tradition with rock energy and jazz sophistication.',
    earlyLife: 'Stephen Ray Vaughan was born on October 3, 1954, in Dallas, Texas, the younger brother of guitarist Jimmie Vaughan. Stevie picked up the guitar at age seven, inspired by his brother\'s playing and the records of Albert King, Muddy Waters, and B.B. King. By his early teens he was performing in local garage bands across Dallas. He dropped out of high school to pursue music full-time, relocating to Austin\'s thriving blues scene in 1972, where he quickly became a fixture in the city\'s clubs.',
    career: 'After years playing Austin clubs like Antone\'s, Vaughan\'s explosive 1982 performance at the Montreux Jazz Festival put him on the international map. David Bowie hired him to play lead guitar on the <em>Let\'s Dance</em> album, though Vaughan left the tour over a contract dispute. His debut album <em>Texas Flood</em> (1983) was a revelation, proving that raw, unfiltered blues guitar could still command a massive audience. He followed it with four more albums in just seven years, each showcasing his extraordinary technical ability and deep emotional feel. His playing drew from Albert King\'s string bending, Jimi Hendrix\'s power, and the elegance of jazz. After conquering addiction in 1986, his playing reached new heights on <em>In Step</em> (1989), widely considered his finest work.',
    legacy: 'Despite a career spanning only seven years of major recordings, Stevie Ray Vaughan is universally regarded as one of the greatest guitarists ever. He revived interest in electric blues at a time when synthesizers and pop dominated the airwaves, inspiring an entire generation of blues and rock guitarists including John Mayer, Kenny Wayne Shepherd, and Gary Clark Jr. He was posthumously inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2015 and the Blues Hall of Fame in 2000. His statue stands on the shore of Lady Bird Lake in Austin, a permanent tribute from the city that shaped him.',
