    genre: 'Blues', nationality: 'American', era: 'Blues / R&B / Soul',
    tagline: 'The matriarch of modern blues and R&B',
    intro: 'Etta James possessed one of the most powerful and versatile voices in American music. Over a career spanning nearly six decades, she moved effortlessly between blues, R&B, soul, jazz, and gospel, bringing raw emotional intensity to everything she sang. Her rendition of "At Last" became one of the most iconic love songs ever recorded, but her catalog runs far deeper, encompassing gritty blues, scorching rock and roll, and tender ballads that reveal the full range of human feeling.',
    earlyLife: 'Born Jamesetta Hawkins on January 25, 1938, in Los Angeles, California, she never knew her father and was raised primarily by foster parents. She began singing in the choir of St. Paul Baptist Church at age five, where choir director James Earle Hines recognized her prodigious talent and gave her vocal training. By her early teens she had moved back to San Francisco with her mother and formed a girl group called the Creolettes, which caught the attention of bandleader Johnny Otis.',
    career: 'After her teenage debut hit "The Wallflower" (an answer song to Hank Ballard\'s "Work With Me Annie"), Etta James signed with Chess Records in 1960 and immediately recorded the material that would define her legacy. The <em>At Last!</em> album showcased her ability to transform pop standards into deeply personal statements. Through the 1960s she recorded a string of blues and R&B classics, culminating in the <em>Tell Mama</em> album cut at FAME Studios in Muscle Shoals. After years of personal struggles, she made a triumphant comeback in the late 1980s and 1990s, recording blues and jazz albums that earned critical acclaim and multiple Grammy Awards. Her voice never lost its fire, and she continued performing into the 2000s.',
    legacy: 'Etta James is widely regarded as one of the greatest vocalists in American music history. Her ability to channel deep emotion through blues, R&B, soul, rock, and jazz influenced generations of singers including Janis Joplin, Christina Aguilera, Adele, and Beyonce. She won six Grammy Awards, was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame (1993), the Blues Hall of Fame (2001), and the Grammy Hall of Fame. Rolling Stone ranked her among the 100 greatest artists of all time and the 25 greatest singers ever. Her music endures as a testament to the power of the human voice to convey joy, heartbreak, and resilience.',
